      <hedline>
        <hl1>For Belgrade, a Fateful Moment</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas P McKenna letter agrees with Gov George W Bush's stand that US forces should be used only to defend the vital interests of America (Oct 7 Anthony Lewis Op-Ed column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Milosevic and Bush,'' by Anthony Lewis (column, Oct. 7):</p>
        <p>Mr. Lewis wants the United States to continue being the world's policeman. This interventionist policy has American troops overcommitted, overseas, and not training to fight wars.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Milosevic and Bush,'' by Anthony Lewis (column, Oct. 7):</p>
        <p>Mr. Lewis wants the United States to continue being the world's policeman. This interventionist policy has American troops overcommitted, overseas, and not training to fight wars.</p>
        <p>Mr. Lewis cites the Balkans as a place where we should be the policeman. Why isn't that a European responsibility? Over the decades, we have spent American lives and dollars to clean up Europe's messes. When are the Europeans going to grow up and take care of themselves?</p>
        <p>The more we do, the less our allies will do for themselves. George W. Bush is right. American armed forces should be used only to defend the vital interests of America.</p>
        <p>THOMAS P. MCKENNA  Montpelier, Vt., Oct. 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
